Source: AP 12 May 2001 [edited
<http://dailynews.yahoo.com/h/ap/20010512/us/foot_and_mouth_military_1.html>

US Military Wary of Foot-And-Mouth
----------------------------------
AUSTIN, Texas: Large military equipment from Great Britain and the
Netherlands might be barred from exercises at Fort Bliss next month because
of the threat of foot-and-mouth disease. Defense Department officials have
forbidden transport of the equipment by land from the port of Beaumont near
Houston to Fort Bliss, a state agriculture official said Saturday. The
equipment has yet to be loaded on cargo ships to come to the United States.
Officials fear the cargo might be contaminated with foot-and-mouth, and
overland transport could bring the equipment into contact with animal herds.
The equipment could still be delivered by air so long as "extreme
precautions" are taken to ensure that troops cannot transmit the disease,
said Beverly Boyd, a spokeswoman for the Texas Department of Agriculture.
The restrictions are part of the government's effort to protect the United
States from foot-and-mouth disease, which has affected livestock in Europe,
particularly Great Britain. Texas has the largest number of cattle, sheep,
and goats in the country, all of which are susceptible to foot-and-mouth
disease.
The military exercises, which include about 25 000 troops representing air
and ground forces from the United States, Great Britain, Netherlands, and
Germany, are scheduled June 15 through June 30 in west Texas and New
Mexico. Equipment from Germany arrived in Beaumont Monday. There's no
problem with that equipment, Boyd said, because there are no confirmed
cases of foot-and-mouth cases in Germany. Still, the equipment was cleaned
and disinfected twice as a precaution before it was loaded in Europe.
[Byline: Kristina Shevory
