[3
Date: Mon 14 May 2001 15:29:53 +0100
From: Ernest Gould <eag@ceh.ac.uk>

I think it is most interesting that when 2 cases of measles (a highly
contagious virus) are introduced into El Salvador, the immediate response
is to immunise and sanitise. I do realise that it is not possible to
"slaughter to control" the disease but presumably there is every
expectation that the immunisation and sanitisation controls will work,
despite the fact that the 2 students carrying measles virus will
undoubtedly have had contact with other humans before the disease was
recognised.
However, this method of controlling FMDV in the UK was not implemented, and
the disease spread widely throughout the country! As a virologist, I would
be surprised if measles is any less contagious than FMDV.
Moreover, measles, like FMDV, is also capable of producing persistent
infections!
Doesn't this argue in favour of immunisation and sanitisation to control FMDV?
---
Dr E A Gould
Institute of Virology and Environmental Microbiology
Mansfield Road, Oxford
OX1 3SR United Kingdom
<eag@ceh.ac.uk>
[Obviously, in the aftermath of the experiences of the UK, France, and The
Netherlands with FMD, the standard veterinary approaches will be up for
reconsideration and 20/20 hindsight expert advice. It will be interesting.
It should be noted the Salvadoran authorities are only talking of
"ring-vaccination," i.e., family and contacts, not regional or national
vaccination, in spite of the country being highly susceptible through its
prior measles-free status. If nothing else, this would argue that FMDv has
a much greater spreading capacity than the human measles virus; this is
certainly the case with the other mammalian morbilliviruses for distemper
and rinderpest. Of course the aphthoviruses have some fundamental
differences from the morbilliviruses.
Secondly I would argue that veterinarians are philosophically different
from physicians, though we use the same tools. This difference can cause
confusion and misunderstanding. While a physician's first objective is to
do no harm, ours is to minimise the costs (of disease) either to the owner
or to the community. It is worded somewhat differently in the
veterinarian's oath ... "for the benefit of society"; but I am not off the
mark. The FMD procedures are aimed at minimising the economic costs, not
minimising the disease. Usually a slaughter policy efficiently achieves
this. Plus, until recently, our inability to differentiate between
naturally-FMDv-infected stock and the vaccinated stock constrained vaccine
use. I can foresee the UK experience being rerun many times as a
computerised war game to determine what should have been done with and
without the constraints of the time -- incomplete knowledge of the initial
wide national spread, bureaucratic constraints, limited organizational
skills and abilities, and facilities. I suspect that these games will need
better models than are currently available and a better knowledge of the
disease. For example, FMD in sheep performs very differently from the MAFF
presumptions used. Time will tell. - Mod.MHJ
